{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 17:12:33.423173", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network reachability, device localization, and root-cause analysis\n\nSummary / overall health\n- User-access subnets (10.1.x.x and 10.2.x.x) are largely healthy: intra-subnet and inter-subnet host pings succeed with low loss and reasonable RTTs in most cases.\n- Server-farm / infrastructure network (10.200.0.0/24) is healthy internally: web servers, load‑balancer, DHCP and DNS on the server LAN can reach each other with low latency.\n- However, hosts in the 10.1/10.2 networks do not appear to have end-to-end IP reachability to the server farm (10.200.0.0/24); server routes are missing from the core routers' routing tables. This is a clear anomaly: server network is isolated from the rest of the enterprise.\n\nKey evidence and observations\n1. Reachability summary (selected)\n   - Many host-to-host pings within 10.1.x.x and 10.2.x.x succeeded (0% loss, typical RTTs a few ms).\n   - Pings from many hosts to server-farm addresses (10.200.x.x and backend 20.200.x.x) show status \"unknown\" in the reachability dump — i.e., the automated ping attempts to server addresses from those hosts were not successful/available. At the same time, server-side pings between servers and between servers and load balancer/dhcp/dns succeeded with low latency.\n   - Example indicative results:\n     - host_2_2_1_1 → many 10.1/10.2 hosts: OK (0% loss).\n     - host_2_2_1_1 → web_server_0 / load_balancer / dhcp_server / dns_server: status unknown (no successful test recorded).\n     - Server-to-server and server-to-load_balancer/dhcp/dns: OK (0% loss, RTT ~1 ms).\n\n2. Server LAN routing and server-router state\n   - server_access_router (the router connected to 10.200.0.0/24) shows 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected on br0:\n     - \"O   10.200.0.0/24 [110/10] is directly connected, br0\"\n   - Server-side services and inter-server connectivity are functioning; the server_access_router knows the server subnet locally, but that network is not present in the core routers' route tables.\n\n3. Core routing tables and OSPF propagation\n   - router_core_1's routing table: contains OSPF routes for 10.1.x.x and 10.2.x.x networks but no 10.200.0.0/24 entry. (i.e., core1 has no route to server-farm).\n   - router_core_2's routing table: likewise shows 10.1.x.x and 10.2.x.x networks but no 10.200.0.0/24 route.\n   - Attempt to query router_core_3 failed (could not show routes).\n\n4. FRR (routing daemon) on router_core_3\n   - systemctl status on router_core_3 shows FRR service is inactive (dead):\n     - \"frr.service ... Active: inactive (dead)\"\n   - frr_show_ip_route for router_core_3 failed (\"Exiting: failed to connect to any daemons\").\n   - This indicates FRR is not running on router_core_3, so OSPF on that device is not operating.\n\nLocalization — faulty device(s)\n- Primary faulty device: router_core_3 — FRR (the routing daemon) is inactive on that router.\n  - Evidence: systemctl shows FRR inactive/dead; cannot query FRR on that router; other core routers do not have route to 10.200.0.0/24 while the server_access_router has it directly connected.\n- Affected area: OSPF routing domain between server_access_router and the core/distribution routers (i.e., the path that should propagate the 10.200.0.0/24 advertisement into the rest of the network).\n\nRoot cause analysis\n- Likely root cause: FRR daemon on router_core_3 is stopped/crashed/stalled. Because router_core_3 is the connection point (per topology) between server_access_router and the core network, its FRR inactivity prevents OSPF adjacency(s) and prevents the server_access_router's advertisement of 10.200.0.0/24 from being propagated into the core OSPF domain.\n- Consequence: Core routers (router_core_1, router_core_2) lack routes to 10.200.0.0/24; hosts in 10.1/10.2 cannot reach the server farm; server LAN remains internally reachable (local connectivity intact) but is isolated from user networks.\n\nAdditional observations / secondary anomalies\n- Some host-to-host paths show elevated packet loss or high jitter in the reachability dataset:\n  - Example: host_2_1_2_2 → host_1_1_1_1 shows 75% loss; several other paths from host_2_1_2_2 show 25–50% loss to a subset of hosts. These are localized performance/packet-loss anomalies on specific host paths and should be investigated separately.\n  - Some hosts report high rtt_mdev or wide RTT spread on certain inter-subnet pings (suggests transient congestion, load, or path asymmetry on those links).\n- The internals of the server farm (web0..web3, load_balancer, dhcp_server, dns_server) show good mutual reachability — this confirms the issue is routing/advertisement rather than server NICs or bridging.\n\nConfidence and impact\n- Confidence: High that the root cause is FRR being down on router_core_3 and that this is the reason server-farm routes are not propagated. Evidence includes systemctl showing inactive FRR, inability to query router_core_3 FRR, absence of 10.200.0.0/24 in core routers' route tables, and server_access_router showing 10.200 directly connected.\n- Impact: Hosts in user subnets cannot resolve/access services hosted in 10.200.0.0/24 (DNS, web99.local, webX.local, DHCP relay to central server) — major service outage for end-users. Server farm and its internal services themselves are still operational.\n\nRecommended diagnostic follow-ups (no remedies provided here)\n- Confirm OSPF neighbor/adjacency status on server_access_router and on the two core routers (router_core_1 and router_core_2) to verify which adjacencies to router_core_3 are down.\n- Collect FRR logs and system logs from router_core_3 to determine why the frr.service is inactive (crash, config error, manual stop, resource exhaustion).\n- Re-run targeted pings/traceroutes from representative user hosts toward 10.200.x.x addresses and capture traceroute to see the exact hop where traffic is dropped.\n- Correlate any recent config changes or events on router_core_3 (package/OS updates, config pushes, resource alerts) around the time FRR stopped.\n\nShort conclusion\n- Primary fault: router_core_3 is not running FRR -> OSPF not functioning on that device -> server_access_router's server-farm network not propagated to the core -> user hosts cannot reach the server farm. Secondary packet-loss anomalies exist on some host-to-host paths and should be investigated separately.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 32984, "output_tokens": 2805, "total_tokens": 35789, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 32512}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1216}}}
